               <head>Fath Ali Shah's letter to Gore Ouseley on terms of new treaty</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Farmān</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85100074 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85104368 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2009117611 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008115489" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_4246-item1">
                     <note>
                        <p>Edict or farmān with the seal of <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_51026511" ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/n99910124" role="pat">Fatḥ ʿAlī Shāh</persName> (dated 1217/1802) and invocation,
addressesed to  <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_44733962" ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/n93023258" role="rcp">Gore Ouseley</persName>, the English ambassador, noting the submission of his petition and good service, alongside the courtier, Mīrzā Abū al-Ḥasan Khān; terms for new treaty under royal consideration, Ouseley's questions regarding terms will be answered; maktūbāt or documents will be issued, some farmāns with explanatory appendices or z̲ayl, which Ouseley may complete; Ouseley to speedily submit his terms in petitions 
                        </p>
                        <p>Interlinear lists of weapons (tūp, shamshīr, ṭapānchah, chaqmāq'sāz, ) inserted towards the end of the edict </p>
                        <p>Additional terms and conditions inscribed in right margin </p>
                        <p>Dated: Shaʿbān 1228/August 1813 </p>
                        <p>Shikastah āmīz; gold ṭughrā style invocation and shikastah āmīz invocation at top </p>
                        <p>Irregularly cropped, stained, old fold lines, and creases</p>
                        <p>IOL stamp: 1 May 1919
</p>
                        <p>Seal impressions on the reverse: Muḥammad Ḥusayn 1214; Muḥammad Yūsuf; Muḥammad 1222; Muḥammad Ṣādiq 1218; Muḥammad Shafīʿ; ʿAbd al-Vahhāb al-Mūsavī 1225; Faraydūn [Mīrzā] 1224; Muḥammad Kāẓim 12...(?); Zayn al-ʿĀbidīn </p>
                        <p>Watermark on very poor quality paper with visible thinning: Cyrillic inscriptions without visible date</p>
                     </note>
